For this question to be true I considered 3 scenario's that could happen: a coup, death, or voluntary resignation. The chance of an incumbent dying in office in a given year (Based on the last 20 years) is about 1,25% (50 dead leaders over 20 years and +- 200 countries) Change of a Coup in South America and the Caribbean the last 20 years was 0,8% ( 7 coups in 20 years over +-40 counties) The same change in the previous century was around 2%. Since Venezuela's situation in my opinion resembles that of Latin America counties over the whole 20th century more closely than a Latin American country in the 21st century I raise the probability of a coup from 0,8% to 1,5%, closer to the 20th century average. The change of a voluntary stepdown I consider too small to measure. Adding the percentages up gives a change of Maduro not making 1-1-2021 at 2,75%. Since there are only 15 Days left in this year this gives an probability of around 0.1%. I round this up to 1% - never ascribe zero possibility.

There have been few signs of Venezuela's military joining the opposition, and Maduro has used a number of "coup-proofing" techniques to ensure that even if some do, there are others who will still support him. This includes patronage, overlapping military services, and personally loyal militia type groups. While some research suggests that competitive militaries may in fact further the likelihood of military units sitting out a coup, it is also likely to ensure some dissention between military officers. International intervention also seems unlikely, although the lack of support from friendly regimes like Russia does appear negative.

Maduro holds a lot of control over the Venezuelan Presidency, Courts, and the Military. He is not particularly old nor have there been very many, possibly zero, legitimate assassination attempts against him. Frequent Purges and using the courts to seize/puppet opposition political parties (although not the main one, led by Guaido) mean he is unlikely to face revolutions from inside the Venezuela. There is also very little political appetite for invasions / externally supported coups outside of Venezuela. With the US, SA, and EU mostly on the side of Guaido, and Russia, China, and the Middle East mostly backing Maduro's Regime. It is fairly unlikely that any states against Maduro will risk the Ire of the World Powers backing him. The Wild Card however, is that Trump has an election coming up and may see an invasion/intervention in Venezuela as a good way to wag the dog (like he did with Soleimani and the Impeachment trial). On the other hand, Trump does seem to be warming up to Maduro (at the manipulation of Putin)

There's a humanitarian and a political crisis in Venezuela, which is causing tension on a global scale, as well as a national scale for their country. Unfortunately, the failed paramilitary operation has put Guaido (Maduro's competition and the interim president) in a precarious position. It has also prompted Maduro to do more to ensure he stays in power. These are conflicts that will likely increase in intensity over the next year or so until they come to a head. They'll also likely affect relations between other countries even more. Despite this, it's unlikely all of this will come to a head and Maduro will be completely removed as Venezuela's president within the next six months.

Maduro has held on to power for more than a year, despite significant pressure from the international community. It is unlikely that a more coordinated or concerted international effort to remove the Maduro administration will emerge in the next six months due to the COVID-19 pandemic. However, the same events that alleviate international pressure on Maduro also undercut the likelihood of international support from partners like Russia or Iran and make the administration more vulnerable to domestic pressures. At present, the Maduro administration with the help of law enforcement and the Venezuelan military appears capable of holding onto power. But an increasing COVID-19 death toll, and the attendant disorganization to government institutions dealing with the virus in their ranks, could quickly leave the Maduro administration teetering and a well-organized revolutionary movement might well be able to seize the opportunity.

The greatest threat to Maduro would probably be widespread dissatisfaction combined with a public health crisis due to covid-19. Going off of US actuarial tables [1], we'd predict a little under half a percent chance that a man of Maduro's age passes away in the coming year. Even assuming that he gets substantially better medical care than the average American or Venezuelan, head of state is a fairly risky job, so I'm happy bumping that up to a 1%. The CoupCast model from One Earth Future predicts a 1.8% chance of a coup in Venezuela this year [2] (assuming that we don't already count the Silvercorp, ah, incident). With the year already partially done, I'm happy blending that in in with other internal security risks to 2%, and I'm sure there are some things I haven't thought of, so I'd add a little fuzz factor.
